<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<task id="022" project="code-quality-and-assurance-r1">
  <metadata>
    <title>Implement Claude Code PostToolUse Lint Hook</title>
    <phase>3: Automation Pipelines</phase>
    <status>pending</status>
    <estimated-hours>2</estimated-hours>
    <dependencies>011, 016</dependencies>
    <blocks>043</blocks>
    <tags>automation, hooks, claude-code, linting</tags>
  </metadata>

  <prompt>
    Create a Claude Code PostToolUse hook script at scripts/quality/post-edit-lint.sh. The hook detects
    the file type of the edited file and runs the appropriate linter: .cs files use dotnet format
    --include {file}, .ts and .tsx files use npx eslint {file}, and .ps1 files use Invoke-ScriptAnalyzer
    -Path {file}. Register the hook in .claude/settings.json. The hook must complete in under 5 seconds
    per file and must handle errors gracefully without crashing the Claude Code session.
  </prompt>

  <role>
    DevOps engineer specializing in Claude Code hooks and developer tooling. Expert in shell scripting
    for cross-platform environments and integrating linters into automated workflows.
  </role>

  <goal>
    A registered PostToolUse hook that automatically lints each file immediately after Claude Code edits
    it, providing instant feedback on code quality issues. The hook must be fast (under 5 seconds),
    error-tolerant, and produce clear output that Claude Code can read and respond to.
  </goal>

  <context>
    <background>
      Claude Code's Hooks system (February 2026) allows custom shell commands to fire at specific
      points in a session. The PostToolUse hook fires after any tool use matching the configured
      matcher. For edit operations, this enables instant per-file linting without waiting for a
      full CI run.

      The hook receives context via stdin (JSON with tool name, file path, and result). The script
      extracts the file path, determines the file type, and dispatches to the correct linter:
      - .cs → `dotnet format --include {file} --verify-no-changes` (verify mode, report violations)
      - .ts/.tsx → `npx eslint {file} --format compact` (compact format for easy parsing)
      - .ps1 → `Invoke-ScriptAnalyzer -Path {file} -Severity Warning,Error` via pwsh

      Critical: The hook MUST NOT cause Claude Code to crash or hang. Use a strict timeout (4s)
      with `timeout` command. Exit with 0 even on lint violations (violations are advisory, not
      blocking). Only exit non-zero if the linter itself errors (e.g., file not found, config error).

      The hook is registered in .claude/settings.json under hooks.PostToolUse with matcher "Edit".
      The existing .claude/settings.json must be read first to understand current structure before
      modifying it.
    </background>
    <relevant-files>
      <file>scripts/quality/post-edit-lint.sh (create)</file>
      <file>.claude/settings.json (modify — register hook)</file>
    </relevant-files>
  </context>

  <constraints>
    <constraint source="spec">Hook MUST complete in under 5 seconds per file. Use `timeout 4` command wrapper on all linter invocations.</constraint>
    <constraint source="spec">Hook MUST NOT crash the Claude Code session. All errors must be caught and reported as non-fatal. Exit code 0 for lint violations, non-zero only for hook infrastructure errors.</constraint>
    <constraint source="spec">Hook must handle the case where a linter is not installed (dotnet not in PATH, ESLint not installed, PSScriptAnalyzer not available) by skipping gracefully with a warning message.</constraint>
    <constraint source="spec">Only the Edit tool matcher should trigger this hook — do not fire on Read, Bash, or other tool uses.</constraint>
    <constraint source=".claude/settings.json">Must read existing .claude/settings.json before modifying. Preserve all existing keys and values. Merge the new hook registration into the existing hooks structure.</constraint>
  </constraints>

  <knowledge>
    <files>
      <file>projects/code-quality-and-assurance-r1/spec.md</file>
    </files>
  </knowledge>

  <steps>
    <step order="1">Read .claude/settings.json to understand the current structure, existing hooks (if any), and permission settings that must be preserved.</step>
    <step order="2">Design the hook script structure: read stdin JSON to extract the file path argument, use file extension detection (basename and case/if logic) to dispatch to the correct linter.</step>
    <step order="3">Create scripts/quality/ directory if it does not exist. Create scripts/quality/post-edit-lint.sh with bash shebang and executable permissions.</step>
    <step order="4">Implement the stdin parsing section: use `jq` or `python3 -c "import json,sys; d=json.load(sys.stdin); print(d.get('tool_input',{}).get('file_path',''))"` to extract the file path from the PostToolUse JSON payload.</step>
    <step order="5">Implement the .cs branch: check if dotnet is available in PATH, then run `timeout 4 dotnet format --include "$FILE" --verify-no-changes 2>&1`. Capture and print output. Exit 0 regardless of violations.</step>
    <step order="6">Implement the .ts/.tsx branch: check if npx is available, then run `timeout 4 npx eslint "$FILE" --format compact 2>&1`. Capture and print output. Exit 0 on violations.</step>
    <step order="7">Implement the .ps1 branch: check if pwsh is available, then run `timeout 4 pwsh -Command "Invoke-ScriptAnalyzer -Path '$FILE' -Severity Warning,Error | Format-Table -AutoSize" 2>&1`. Capture and print output.</step>
    <step order="8">Add the fallback case: if the file extension is not .cs, .ts, .tsx, or .ps1, exit 0 silently (no linter for this file type).</step>
    <step order="9">Add a global error trap at the top of the script: `set -euo pipefail` with a `trap 'echo "Hook error (non-fatal): $BASH_COMMAND" >&2; exit 0' ERR` to ensure the hook never crashes Claude Code.</step>
    <step order="10">Update .claude/settings.json: add the PostToolUse hook entry under the hooks key with matcher "Edit" and command pointing to the script. Use an absolute path or a path relative to the repository root.</step>
    <step order="11">Verify the script is executable: `chmod +x scripts/quality/post-edit-lint.sh`. Document how to test the hook manually.</step>
    <step order="12">Update TASK-INDEX.md: change task 022 status from pending to completed.</step>
  </steps>

  <outputs>
    <output type="file">scripts/quality/post-edit-lint.sh</output>
    <output type="file">.claude/settings.json (updated with hook registration)</output>
  </outputs>

  <acceptance-criteria>
    <criterion>scripts/quality/post-edit-lint.sh exists and is executable (chmod +x)</criterion>
    <criterion>Script correctly dispatches to dotnet format for .cs files, eslint for .ts/.tsx files, PSScriptAnalyzer for .ps1 files</criterion>
    <criterion>Script exits 0 on lint violations (violations are advisory, not blocking)</criterion>
    <criterion>Script handles missing linter tools gracefully with a warning and exit 0</criterion>
    <criterion>Global error trap prevents any hook error from propagating to Claude Code</criterion>
    <criterion>timeout 4 wraps all linter invocations to enforce the 5-second budget</criterion>
    <criterion>.claude/settings.json contains PostToolUse hook registration with matcher "Edit"</criterion>
    <criterion>All existing .claude/settings.json keys and values are preserved (no accidental deletions)</criterion>
    <criterion>TASK-INDEX.md updated to reflect task completion</criterion>
  </acceptance-criteria>
</task>
